data.content:
California
California is a state where praseodymium, neodymium, and other rare-earth compounds are produced.

Utah
Utah is a state where rare-earth compounds are produced.

China
China is a leading country in rare earth mining, processing, and production, with 44 million tons of reserves.<SEP>China is a source of import data regarding rare-earth materials.<SEP>China is a major source of rare-earth compounds and metals, accounting for 70% of US imports.

Australia
Australia has 3.3 million tons of Joint Ore Reserves Committee-compliant or equivalent reserves of rare-earth materials.<SEP>Australia is a major producer and holder of rare earth reserves, with 5.7 million tons of reserves.

U.S. Census Bureau
The U.S. Census Bureau is a source of data regarding rare-earth material production and imports/exports.<SEP>The U.S. Census Bureau is a source of data related to rare earth content and production estimates.

Argus Media Group
Argus Media Group, specifically Argus Non-Ferrous Markets, provides data related to non-ferrous materials.

Zen Innovations
Zen Innovations, through Global Trade Tracker, is a source of estimated data based on reported import data for China.

Joint Ore Reserves Committee
The Joint Ore Reserves Committee sets standards for reporting ore reserves, used for Australian data.

2023
Year in which 1,920 tons of rare-earth compounds were produced domestically.

2024
Year in which 7,600 tons of rare-earth compounds were produced domestically.

Rare-Earth Compounds
A category of materials being produced, imported, and exported, with data tracked by various organizations.

Praseodymium
A rare-earth element produced in California.<SEP>Praseodymium is a rare earth metal often used with neodymium.

Neodymium
A rare-earth element produced in California.

Hong Kong
Included in import/export data figures.

Gross Weight
Measurement unit for material quantities.

Appendix B
Contains definitions used in the text.

Appendix C
Contains resource and reserve definitions and data source information.

Production Quota
Represents the maximum allowable production level.

Undocumented Production
Production not officially recorded or reported.

United States
The United States is a significant country with rare earth production and resources, with 1.9 million tons of rare earth resources.

Canada
Canada has substantial rare earth resources, exceeding 14 million tons.

Russia
Russia has rare earth reserves totaling 3.8 million tons.

Nigeria
Nigeria shows increasing rare earth production with 7,200 tons in 2023 and 13,000 in 2024.

Thailand
Thailand has experienced an increase in rare earth production, with 3,600 tons in 2023 and 13,000 in 2024.

Vietnam
Vietnam holds substantial rare earth reserves of 3.5 million tons.

Rare Earths
Rare earths are a group of elements mined and processed for various industrial applications, with significant US production and import reliance.<SEP>Rare earths are mineral commodities with varying applications, but minable concentrations are less common.

World total
The world total of rare earth production is approximately 376,000 tons (rounded) in 2023 and 390,000 tons in 2024.

Monazite
Monazite is a phosphate mineral stockpiled as a rare-earth concentrate in the southeastern United States.<SEP>Monazite is a phosphate mineral that often contains rare earth elements.

Bastnaesite
Bastnaesite is a rare earth fluorocarbonate mineral.<SEP>Bastnaesite is a rare-earth fluorocarbonate mineral mined as a primary product in Mountain Pass, CA.

Xenotime
Xenotime is a rare earth phosphate mineral.

Cerium Compounds
Cerium compounds are chemicals containing cerium, a rare earth element.

Lanthanum
Lanthanum is a rare earth element used in various applications.

Neodymium-Praseodymium Oxide
Neodymium-Praseodymium Oxide is a compound used in magnets.

Neodymium-Iron-Boron Magnet Block
Neodymium-Iron-Boron Magnet Block is a type of permanent magnet.

Samarium-Cobalt Alloy
Samarium-Cobalt Alloy is a high-performance magnet alloy.

Scandium
Scandium is a rare earth metal used in alloys and fuel cells.

Yttrium
Yttrium is a rare earth metal used in various applications.

Malaysia
Malaysia is a source of rare-earth compounds and metals, accounting for 13% of US imports.

Japan
Japan is a source of rare-earth compounds and metals, accounting for 6% of US imports.

Estonia
Estonia is a source of rare-earth compounds and metals, accounting for 5% of US imports.

Permanent Magnets
Permanent magnets are a key end use of rare earths, with some sourced as embedded components in finished goods.

Batteries
Batteries are a source for recycling rare earths.

Fluorescent Lamps
Fluorescent lamps are a source for recycling rare earths.

Mountain Pass, CA
Mountain Pass, CA, is the location of a mine producing Bastnaesite.

Southeastern United States
The Southeastern United States is a region where Monazite is stockpiled.

US Imports
Represents the total amount of rare earth compounds and metals imported into the United States.

Rare-Earth Fluorocarbonate
The chemical composition of Bastnaesite, a primary rare-earth mineral.

Phosphate Mineral
The chemical composition of Monazite, a rare-earth containing mineral.

Heavy-Mineral-Sand Concentrates
A type of mineral concentrate that can contain Monazite.

Cerium Oxide
A specific rare-earth compound with a stated price of $1/kg.

Dysprosium Oxide
A specific rare-earth compound with a stated price of $260/kg.

Europium Oxide
A specific rare-earth compound with a stated price of $27/kg.

Lanthanum Oxide
A specific rare-earth compound with a stated price of $1/kg.

Mischmetal
An alloy containing cerium and lanthanum, priced at $5/kg.

Neodymium Oxide
A specific rare-earth compound with a stated price of $56/kg.

Terbium Oxide
A specific rare-earth compound with a stated price of $810/kg.

Ferrocerium Alloys
Alloys that include Ferrocerium, a rare-earth metal.

Scandium & Yttrium
Rare-earth metals also imported and exported.
